== In infinite dimensions ==
Below, all vector spaces are over either the real numbers formula_54 or the complex numbers formula_88

If formula_219 is a topological vector space, the space of continuous linear functionals — the — is often simply called the dual space. If formula_219 is a Banach space, then so is its (continuous) dual. To distinguish the ordinary dual space from the continuous dual space, the former is sometimes called the . In finite dimensions, every linear functional is continuous, so the continuous dual is the same as the algebraic dual, but in infinite dimensions the continuous dual is a proper subspace of the algebraic dual.

A linear functional on a (not necessarily locally convex) topological vector space is continuous if and only if there exists a continuous seminorm on such that formula_221

=== Characterizing closed subspaces ===
Continuous linear functionals have nice properties for analysis: a linear functional is continuous if and only if its kernel is closed, and a non-trivial continuous linear functional is an open map, even if the (topological) vector space is not complete.

==== Hyperplanes and maximal subspaces ====

A vector subspace formula_222 of formula_87 is called maximal if formula_224 (meaning formula_225 and formula_226) and does not exist a vector subspace formula_227 of formula_87 such that formula_229 A vector subspace formula_222 of formula_87 is maximal if and only if it is the kernel of some non-trivial linear functional on formula_87 (that is, formula_233 for some linear functional formula_50 on formula_87 that is not identically ). An affine hyperplane in formula_87 is a translate of a maximal vector subspace. By linearity, a subset formula_237 of formula_87 is a affine hyperplane if and only if there exists some non-trivial linear functional formula_50 on formula_87 such that formula_241 
If formula_50 is a linear functional and formula_243 is a scalar then formula_244 This equality can be used to relate different level sets of formula_245 Moreover, if formula_246 then the kernel of formula_50 can be reconstructed from the affine hyperplane formula_248 by formula_249

==== Relationships between multiple linear functionals ====

Any two linear functionals with the same kernel are proportional (i.e. scalar multiples of each other). 
This fact can be generalized to the following theorem.

